          "body": "The second vision (5:5-11) operates on a different register from the first. Where the scroll targeted individual sinners, the ephah targets corporate, systemic wickedness. The ephah was the standard commercial dry measure — the instrument of grain transactions, merchant dealings, the infrastructure of the market. The prophets had already associated dishonest ephah-weights with covenant betrayal: Amos 8:5 ('making the ephah small and the shekel great, falsifying the scales by deceit') and Micah 6:10-11 ('Are there yet treasures of wickedness in the house of the wicked, and the short measure that is an abomination?'). Zechariah picks up that prophetic tradition and takes it one step further: the measuring basket itself becomes the container for the personified spirit of market wickedness. The woman inside is labeled not merely 'a sinner' but '*rishah*' — Wickedness in the abstract, the animating spirit behind the systemic corruption. This is among the earliest canonical examples of evil personified as a female figure enthroned — imagery that Revelation 17 will develop into the harlot Babylon riding the beast. The lead cover (5:7-8) is divine containment: heavier than the woman can lift, pressed down by the angel with controlled force."
