          "title": "Shinar — the exile of Wickedness and the antithesis of Zion",
          "body": "The chapter's final movement is the transportation of Wickedness to Shinar and the building of a temple for her there (5:11). This destination is the most theologically freighted element in the chapter. Shinar appears four times in the canonical narrative before Zechariah: the location of Babel (Genesis 10:10; 11:2), where organized human autonomy against God began; the land of Nimrod's kingdom (Genesis 10:8-10); the origin of Amraphel king of Shinar (Genesis 14:1); and the land where Nebuchadnezzar brought the vessels of God's temple (Daniel 1:2 — the only other exilic use). In each case, Shinar is the anti-Zion: the place of human self-deification, of kingdoms built against God, of sacred objects profaned. When Wickedness is enthroned on her pedestal in Shinar's temple, the vision is not merely geographic but eschatological — it is the gathering of all that opposes God into its proper domain, away from the covenant land, ready for ultimate judgment. The two temples — God's house being rebuilt in Jerusalem and Wickedness's house being prepared in Shinar — stand in permanent canonical antithesis. That antithesis reaches its resolution only in Revelation 21-22 (the new Jerusalem) and Revelation 18 (the fall of Babylon)."
