        "number": 3,
        "title": "The stork-winged transport — Wickedness exiled between heaven and earth",
        "range": "5:9",
        "excerpt": "Then I lifted up my eyes and looked, and there two women were coming out with the wind in their wings; and they had wings like the wings of a stork, and they lifted up the ephah between the earth and the heavens.",
        "body": "The third movement of the chapter introduces two new figures — women with stork wings, wind (*ruach*) driving their flight, lifting the sealed ephah into the space between earth and heaven. The image is deliberately spectacular: the transport of Wickedness is not a human political operation or a gradual social reform. It is a supernaturally powered, divinely orchestrated removal.\n\nThe identification of the two winged women has generated interpretive debate. Thomas McComiskey (*The Minor Prophets*, vol. 3) and Joyce Baldwin (*Haggai, Zechariah, Malachi*, TOTC) both note that their identity is left deliberately open in the text — they are agents of the removal, neither praised nor condemned. The stork (*chasidah*) is an interesting choice of image: the word shares a root with *hesed* (covenant love, faithfulness), though most scholars resist pressing that etymology too far in this context. What the stork image conveys is migratory power — the stork is a large, strong, migratory bird capable of sustained flight over great distances. These are not small birds; the imagery suggests irresistible lifting force.\n\nThe *ruach* (wind, spirit) in their wings connects the transport to divine empowerment. The same word *ruach* that denotes the Spirit of God (Genesis 1:2; Zechariah 4:6 — 'not by might nor by power, but by My Spirit') drives the removal of Wickedness. This is not coincidental. The purging of the land and the building of the temple are both Spirit-operations (Zechariah 4:6), and the wind-driven flight of the ephah-carriers places the exile of Wickedness within the same divine empowerment framework.\n\nThe liminal space — 'between the earth and the heavens' — is significant. The ephah is neither on earth (where it has been operating) nor in heaven (where it does not belong). It is in transit, in the custody of supernatural agents, on its way to its appointed destination. The geography of the transit is itself a statement: Wickedness has been lifted out of the covenant land but has not yet arrived at its final resting place. The chapter is not yet finished.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ruach* (wind/spirit, v.9) — deliberately ambiguous; the same word used for the Spirit of God in 4:6. *Chasidah* (stork, v.9) — a large migratory bird; the root connection to *hesed* is noted by some commentators (Motyer) but should not be pressed into the interpretation without further contextual support. *Bayin ha'erets uvein hashamayim* — between the earth and between the heavens — the liminal transport zone."
