        "number": 4,
        "title": "Shinar — Wickedness enthroned in its proper domain",
        "range": "5:10-11",
        "excerpt": "To build a temple for her in the land of Shinar; and when it is prepared, she will be set there on her own pedestal.",
        "body": "The chapter's final verse answers Zechariah's question — 'Where are they taking the ephah?' — with a destination that is a canonical thunderclap: the land of Shinar. Every biblically literate reader in Zechariah's audience would have heard the resonance immediately. Shinar is the location of Babel (Genesis 10:10; 11:2), the first organized human project of self-deification against God. It is the land where Nebuchadnezzar took the vessels of God's temple (Daniel 1:2) — the same vessels Cyrus returned to Jerusalem in 538 BC, whose return preceded Zechariah's ministry by only nineteen years. Wickedness is being sent back to the land that sent the exiles.\n\nThe destination is not merely geographic but theological. A *bet* (house, temple) will be built for Wickedness in Shinar, and she will be set on her own *mekhunah* (pedestal, base). The word *mekhunah* is used elsewhere in the Old Testament for the bases of the bronze lavers in Solomon's temple (1 Kings 7:27-39) — a sacred installation term. In Shinar, Wickedness receives what God refuses to give her in Israel: a shrine, a throne, an installation on a prepared base. The irony is deliberate and biting. God is building His temple in Jerusalem (Zechariah 1:16; 4:9); Wickedness gets its temple in Babylon. The two temples stand in permanent antithesis.\n\nThe theological logic of the vision's ending is not that Wickedness is being made comfortable — it is that it is being removed from where it does not belong (the covenant land) and confined to where it does belong (Babylon, the anti-God civilization of the canon). This is a pattern of divine ordering: the wilderness is for demons (Luke 11:24; Revelation 18:2); the outer darkness is for those who are cast out (Matthew 8:12); Babylon is for Wickedness. The confinement is a form of judgment, not a concession. As Keller observed in a different context, God's justice does not require immediate annihilation — sometimes it requires containment, isolation, and the preparation of a final reckoning that Revelation 18 will execute.\n\nFor Zechariah's post-exilic audience, the vision offered a profound pastoral word: the wickedness they saw operating in their midst was not going to be a permanent resident of the covenant community. God had seen it, named it, contained it, and was in the process of removing it. The land was being prepared for His permanent return — not by the people's moral improvement alone, but by God's direct intervention. The same God who dispatched the flying scroll into individual households was also managing the removal of systemic evil from the land. Both operations belong to the same divine program: purging the land for the return of the divine glory (cf. Zechariah 2:10-11; 8:3).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shinar* — Babylon, Genesis 10:10; 11:2; Daniel 1:2. *Bet* (house/temple, v.11) — the same word used for the temple being rebuilt in Jerusalem throughout Haggai and Zechariah; the parallel is intentional. *Mekhunah* (pedestal, base, v.11) — used of the bronze laver stands in Solomon's temple (1 Kings 7:27); sacred installation language applied ironically to Wickedness's throne in Babylon. *Nuach* (she will be set, placed, v.11) — to rest, to be set down in a place of permanence; same root as Noah (*noach*)."
